# Global Architecture Boundaries (ROOT CONTRACT)

This file is the SINGLE SOURCE OF TRUTH for all GLOBAL dependency rules in the system.

All subsystem boundary rules inherit from this contract.

UI-specific rules are delegated to ui-boundaries.mdc.

---

# 1. Core Dependency Direction (ABSOLUTE)

System must follow strict inward dependency flow:

app
→ features
→ shared
→ infrastructure (services, api, persistence)

Rule:
- dependencies must always flow downward
- upward imports are forbidden

---

# 2. Feature Isolation (GLOBAL RULE)

- Features must not import other features directly
- Cross-feature communication must go through shared/ or services layer
- Features are isolated business domains

Rule:
- no feature-to-feature coupling

---

# 3. Shared Layer Contract (GLOBAL RULE)

- shared is a domain-agnostic abstraction layer
- shared must not depend on features
- shared must not contain business logic

Rule:
- shared is reusable system infrastructure, not domain logic

---

# 4. Infrastructure Boundaries

- services, API clients, persistence layers belong to infrastructure
- infrastructure must not depend on UI or features
- UI consumes services through defined interfaces only

Rule:
- infrastructure is UI-agnostic

---

# 5. Data Flow Direction (STRICT)

Data must flow in one direction:

infrastructure → services → features → UI

Rule:
- no reverse data flow allowed

---

# 6. Global Coupling Rules

Forbidden:

- implicit cross-module coupling
- hidden shared state between features
- direct dependency chains across multiple features
- circular dependencies

Rule:
- all coupling must be explicit and intentional

---

# 7. Architectural Integrity Rule

- import graph is a first-class architecture constraint
- violations are structural defects, not style issues

Rule:
- architecture is enforced through module boundaries

---

# 8. System Guarantee

If respected:

- zero cross-feature coupling
- predictable dependency graph
- scalable module isolation
- controlled architectural evolution